<subSubSection id="B370BDEB023585B113765B12965C1777" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="7B8B833B12CC4F1BAEA01356F82314A4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C8CAE319923C76ED176590BBD1590082" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5B1F3EAADBD069344A2AC67099DE6F7E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bahiensis">
<emphasis id="D73FE98EED4BF880AB955DAAF3D62020" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea bahiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widespread in eastern Bolivia and Brazil and is typical of disturbed bushy places. It is especially common in NE Brazil but apparently absent south of about 18° latitude except in the Rio de Janeiro region. For an account of its mass flowering after fire in eastern Bolivia, see Wood (2019).
</paragraph>
