<paragraph id="F963FC097A1C62337407DBF25BCB502E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="19C105047AFAD350351057EB456A42B0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="ABB0173DC46C574D87A97EF796F19272" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bahiensis">
<emphasis id="238DCB199FD1910A190D937F8DB0C06A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea bahiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has unique sepals. These are fleshy, very pale, spotted near the base and with prominent green tips, these often with a distinct tooth-like appendage. The exact structure appears to be rather variable and difficult to describe accurately even with the aid of photographs showing details. The compact, shortly pedunculate cymes are also distinctive.
</paragraph>
